<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">17891897</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2007</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>16</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2013</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>21</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">0095-6562</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Print"><Volume>78</Volume><Issue>9</Issue><PubDate><Year>2007</Year><Month>Sep</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Aviation, space, and environmental medicine</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Aviat Space Environ Med</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Caffeine effects on physical and cognitive performance during sustained operations.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>871</StartPage><EndPage>877</EndPage><MedlinePgn>871-7</MedlinePgn></Pagination><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">This study examined caffeine (CAF) effects on physical performance and vigilance during 4 d and 3 nights of sustained operations in Special Forces personnel.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">There were 20 soldiers (28.6 +/- 4.7 yr, 177.6 +/- 7.5 cm, 81.2 +/- 8.0 kg) who were divided equally into placebo (PLAC) and CAF groups. A 4-km run that included three obstacles (OBST) was completed each morning with the performance on Day 2 representing control (CON) after familiarization on Day 1 and an 8-h sleep. From 01:30 to 06:15 of Days 3-5, soldiers performed two 2-h vigilance (VIG) sessions in the field. PLAC or 200 mg of CAF was administered at 21:45 of Days 2-4 and at 01:00, 03:45, and approximately 07:00 on Days 3-5. The run commenced within 30 min of the final dose. Soldiers were provided a 4-h sleep period from 13:30-17:30 during Days 3 and 4.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">VIC during Days 3-5 was greater for CAF vs. PLAC and not different from CON. Total run time was faster for CAF (29.7 +/- 2.0 min) compared with PLAC (30.7 +/- 2.9 min) on Day 3 due to faster completion of OBST (8.7 +/- 0.7 min vs. 9.2 +/- 1.0 min for CAF and PLAC, respectively). Thereafter, run times decreased for both groups on Days 4 and 5 compared with CON due primarily to an increased pace between OBST.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">it was concluded that CAF maintained both vigilance and physical performance during sustained operations that require periods of overnight wakefulness and restricted opportunities for daytime sleep.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>McLellan</LastName><ForeName>Tom M</ForeName><Initials>TM</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Individual Readiness Section, DRDC-Toronto, 1133 Sheppard Avenue West, PO Box 2000, Toronto, Ontario M3M 3B9, Canada. tom.mclellan@drdc-rddc.gc.ca</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kamimori</LastName><ForeName>Gary H</ForeName><Initials>GH</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Voss</LastName><ForeName>David M</ForeName><Initials>DM</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Tate</LastName><ForeName>Charmaine</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Smith</LastName><ForeName>Sarah J R</ForeName><Initials>SJ</Initials></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016449">Randomized Controlled Trial</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>Aviat Space Environ Med</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>7501714</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>0095-6562</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><ChemicalList><Chemical><RegistryNumber>0</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D000697">Central Nervous System Stimulants</NameOfSubstance></Chemical><Chemical><RegistryNumber>3G6A5W338E</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D002110">Caffeine</NameOfSubstance></C